value.value: An abnormal reduction in the amount of radioactive tracer uptake upon hepatobiliary scintigraphy.

definition.value: A normal HBS shows rapid clearance of the radio-tracer from the blood pool. Prompt and uniform hepatic uptake is reached within 5 min, functional visualization of the gall bladder is seen as early as 10 min and bowel activity by 30 to 40 minutes. The presence of tracer in the bowel confirm patency of biliary channels and excludes biliary atresia.

value.value: A pulmonary nodule with calcium deposits. On radiography, these nodules appear dense.

definition.value: Calcification in a pulmonary nodule (PN) on imaging indicates a high probability that the lesion is benign. But not all calcified PN are benign and the differential considerations include a primary central lung carcinoid, metastasis and a primary bronchogenic carcinoma.
Applied to a sign or symptom that is more severe following a meal.

value.value: The appearance of new skin lesions on previously unaffected skin secondary to trauma. This phenomenon is also termed the isomorphic (from Greek, equal shape) response, given the fact that the new lesions that appear are clinically and histologically identical to the patient's underlying cutaneous disease.

definition.value: The Koebner phenomenon is typically associated with preexisting skin disease. Clinical entities that commonly display the Koebner phenomenon include psoriasis, vitiligo, lichen planus. The incidence of Koebnerization ranges broadly within these entities; estimates of the prevalence of the Koebner phenomenon are approximately 11 to 75% in psoriasis and 21 to 62% in vitiligo.

value.value: Glenoid dysplasia is a developmental anomaly of the scapula that is characterized by a bony deficiency of the posteroinferior glenoid and the adjacent scapular neck.

definition.value: Glenoid dysplasia may occur as a primary isolated condition or in association with various syndromes. It is thought to be related to defective ossification of the inferior glenoid precartilage. Radiographs typically demonstrate bilateral, symmetric dysplasia of the scapular neck with a range of associated bony changes. Glenoid dysplasia has been associated with instability and premature glenohumeral arthritis, although the clinical presentation is highly variable. Symptoms are delayed or mitigated as a result of compensatory glenoid labral hyperplasia.

value.value: A past medical history of recently having retracted the penile foreskin for a prolonged period of time. Paraphimosis commonly occurs iatrogenically, when the foreskin is retracted for cleaning, placement of a urinary catheter, a procedure such as a cystoscopy, or for penile examination. Failure to return the retracted foreskin over the glans promptly after the initial retraction can lead to paraphimosis.

definition.value: This can be a risk factor for paraphimosis, a urologic emergency that occurs in uncircumcised males when the foreskin becomes trapped behind the corona of the glans penis.

value.value: Abnormal thickening of the cortex of the clavicle.
Abnormal thickening of the cortex of the mandible.
Minor hypoplasia (developmental undergrowth) of the thumb, whereby all musculoskeletal and neurovascular components of the digit are present, just small in size (Blauth classification).

A type of developmental undergrowth of the thumb, whereby all of the osseous structures are present (may be small), and there is metacarpophalangeal joint ulnar collateral ligament instability and thenar hypoplasia.

A type of developmental undergrowth of the thumb, whereby there are musculotendinous and osseous deficiencies with the carpometacarpal (CMC) joint intact. Absence of active motion at the metacarpophalangeal (MCP) or interphalangeal (IP) joint.

A type of developmental undergrowth of the thumb, whereby there are musculotendinous and osseous deficiencies characterized by basal metacarpal aplasia with deficient carpometacarpal (CMC) joint, and absence of metacarpophalangeal (MCP) or interphalangeal (IP) joint.
A type of developmental undergrowth of the thumb characterized by attachment to the hand only by the skin and digital neurovascular structures.

Multiple multiple, small, well-defined radiodense foci of cortical-like bone in the medullary space parallel to the trabeculae located in the femur. The loci correspond to condensations of the lamellar trabeculae on histology.
Pain or tenderness in the region of the carotid artery.

definition.value: Fay Syndrome is characterized by carotidynia and manifests as an atypical facial neuralgia characterized by an unusual neck pain extending towards the head and associated with carotid artery tenderness. Diagnostic criteria include neck tenderness, elevated carotid pulse without anatomical abnormalities, and neck distension.

value.value: A substantial difference in blood pressure (e.g., 20 mmHg) between the right and left arms.

A congenital anomaly that appears as an amputation at different levels of the leg, e.g. femur, foreleg, ankle or toe. The limb is missing the terminal (distal) segment(s), with preservation of all the segment(s) proximal to the missing segment.
A developmental defect leading to a transverse deficiency with absence of the lower leg (eg tibia and fibula), ankle and foot.
A developmental defect leading to a transverse deficiency with absence of the forearm (eg ulna and radius), wrist and hand.

definition.value: History of having been treateed with a sodium glucose transport inhibitors such as dapagliflozin, empagliflozin, canagliflozin, sglt-i, SGLT2, bexagliflozin, ertugliflozin, sotagliflozin, jardiance, invokana, forxiga, brenzavvy, steglatro, inpefa.
May be a risk factor for SGLT-2i induced diabetic ketoacidosis.

value.value: A benign paroxysmal nonepileptic disorder occurring in healthy children 6 to 48 months of age. The episodes start with a provocation such as emotional upset or minor injury, and might progress to breath holding, cyanosis, and syncope.

definition.value: The presence of a splayed (i.e.,flared) metaphyseal segment of the proximal tibia.

value.value: Delayed maturation and calcification of any of the toe phalanges.

definition.value: A history of ingestion of a relatively high amount of foods containing sorbitol.
Growth of bacteria in a culture dervied from ascites fluid.

value.value: Accumulation of cystine crsytals in the eye. Patients present with crystal accumulation affecting the cornea and conjunctiva, but crystals can also be deposited in the iris, ciliary body, choroid and retinal pigment epithelium (RPE), and lens capsule. Corneal crystal deposition starts in infancy in the anterior periphery of the cornea, and progresses centrally and posteriorly. The crystals, which have a fine, uniform needle-shaped structure, are diffusely distributed within the corneal tissues.

A manifestation of abnormal wound healing in which there is formation of excessive granulation tissue, with the granulation tissue rising above the level of surrounding skin and creating a raised, reddish, moist, and bumpy surface.

definition.value: A small (less than 5 mm in diameter), elevated, circumscribed, solid, palpable mass located in thte mucosa of the oral cavity.

value.value: Abnormally increased degree of goose bump formation, that is, of involuntary formation of bumps on a person's skin at the base of body hairs.

definition.value: Excessive piloerection can be a feature of opioid withdrawal.
A palpable swelling in the scalp caused by an increase in interstitial fluid volume (excess fluid).

value.value: A slightly raised and often reddish serpentine or curvilinear path in the skin.

definition.value: Serpiginous refers to the wavy path of the burrows that is said to resemble the tracks of a snake. These lesions are characteristic of scabies and some other infections.

label.value: Positive brain-tissue rabies nucleic acid test

definition.value: Detection of rabies nucleic acid in brain tissue by a method such as polymerase chain reaction.

label.value: Positive respiratory tract Bordetella pertussis nucleic acid test

definition.value: Detection of Bordetella pertussis PCR nucleic acid in in nasopharyngeal secretions by a method such as polymerase chain reaction.

label.value: Demonstration of acid-fast bacilli in wound tissue

value.value: Demonstration of acid-fast bacilli by microscopic examination of wound tissue. Acid fastness is a physical property that gives a bacterium the ability to resist decolorization by acids during staining procedures.

definition.value: Bacteria displaying acid fastness include: Mycobacterium leprae, M. tuberculosis, M. smegmatis, M. Avium complex, M. kansasii, Nocardia brasiliensis, N. cyriacigeorgica, N. farcinica, and N. nova.

label.value: Positive tissue encapsulated budding yeast test

definition.value: Identification of encapsulated budding yeasts in smears of body fluids, secretions, exudates, or other specimens.

In fixed-tissue specimens, encapsulated yeasts may also be identified and confirmed as cryptococci by positive mucicarmine or Masson-Fontana staining. This finding may suggest a diagnosis of cryptococcosis.
Growth of coccidioidomycosis in a culture derived from skin or an organ.

value.value: Concentration or activity of dihydropteridine reductase (EC 1.6.99.7) below the lower limit of normal. This enzyme can be measured in multiple tissues including leukocytes and erythrocytes.

definition.value: Concentration of transcobalamin I in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal.

value.value: Concentration of cationic trypsinogen in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal.

definition.value: Cationic trypsinogen is one of the several isoforms of trypsinogen. Serum cationic trypsinogen when low, is known to be associated with reduced pancreatic exocrine function in a number of disorders, including Shwachman's syndrome and type 1 diabetes mellitus.

value.value: The activity or concentration of hyaluronidase in the blood circulation is below the lower limit of normal.

label.value: Diminished sulfotransferase activity in cultured fibroblasts

value.value: Rate of proteoglycan sulfation (sulfotransferase activity) is below the lower limit of normal in cultured fibroblasts.

Concentration or activity of alpha-N-acetylglucosaminidase (EC 3.2.1.50) above the upper limit of normal. This enzyme can be measured in multiple tissues including leukocytes and cultured fibroblasts. It is also known as alpha-acetylglucosaminidase, N-acetyl-alpha-D-glucosaminidase, N-acetyl-alpha-glucosaminidase, and alpha-D-2-acetamido-2-deoxyglucosidase.

definition.value: Concentration or activity of alpha-N-acetylglucosaminidase (EC 3.2.1.50) outside of the limits of normal. This enzyme can be measured in multiple tissues including leukocytes and cultured fibroblasts. It is also known as alpha-acetylglucosaminidase, N-acetyl-alpha-D-glucosaminidase, N-acetyl-alpha-glucosaminidase, and alpha-D-2-acetamido-2-deoxyglucosidase.
The concentration of trihydroxycholestanoic acid in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.
The concentration of glyoxylic acid in the blood circulation is above the upper limit of normal.

value.value: Concentration of sepiapterin in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) below the lower limit of normal.

definition.value: Nuclear or cytoplasmic aggregates of stainable substances within hepatocytes.
Presence of abnormal vacuoles (membrane-bound organelles) in the sarcolemma. The vacuoles are often associated with cytoplasmic and occasionally intranuclear eosinophilic inclusions.

Presence of abnormal vacuoles (membrane-bound organelles) in the sarcolemma. On histological staining with hematoxylin and eosin, non-rimmed vacuoles lack the prominent dark border (rim) seen in rimmed vacuoles.
Activity or concentration of glycogen phosphorylase L in the liver below the lower limit of normal.
